  "What is 1 Newton in base units?": "",
  "1 kg·m/s": "",
  "1 kg·m²/s²": "",
  "1 kg/m·s²": "",
  "1 kg·m/s²": "",
  "Derived units are combinations of base units. Newton (N) = kg·m/s² (force). Joule (J) = kg·m²/s² (energy). Watt (W) = J/s (power). Pascal (Pa) = N/m² (pressure). The answer is '1 kg·m/s²'. The other options — '1 kg·m/s', '1 kg·m²/s²', and '1 kg/m·s²' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a non-contact force?": "",
  "Friction between shoes and the floor": "",
  "Gravity pulling an apple downward": "",
  "Tension in a stretched rubber band": "",
  "Normal force from a table surface": "",
  "Non-contact forces act at a distance without physical touch. Gravity is the classic example — it pulls objects toward each other without requiring contact. Friction, tension, and normal force all require surfaces or objects to be in direct contact.": "",
  "What are the arrows in a free-body diagram used to represent?": "",
  "The speed of the object in each direction": "",
  "The temperature changes of the object": "",
  "The magnitude and direction of each force": "",
  "The distance the object has traveled": "",
  "In a free-body diagram, each arrow represents a force. The length of the arrow shows the magnitude (strength) of the force, and the direction of the arrow shows which way the force acts. Longer arrows mean stronger forces.": "",
  "How many forces can act on a single object at the same time?": "",
  "Only one force at a time": "",
  "Exactly two forces at a time": "",
  "Multiple forces can act simultaneously": "",
  "No more than four forces at once": "",
  "Many forces can act on a single object at the same time. For example, a book on a table has gravity pulling it down and the normal force pushing it up. A sliding box may also experience friction and an applied push. The net force is the vector sum of all these forces.": "",
  "What is the definition of a force in physics?": "",
  "A push or pull that can change an object's motion": "",
  "The total energy stored inside an object": "",
  "The rate at which an object covers distance": "",
  "The amount of matter contained in an object": "",
  "A force is defined as a push or pull that acts on an object. Forces can cause an object to start moving, stop moving, speed up, slow down, or change direction. Force is measured in Newtons (N).": "",
  "What does the term 'net force' mean?": "",
  "The strongest individual force on an object": "",
  "The combined effect of all forces acting on an object": "",
  "The force that always points downward on objects": "",
  "A force applied only by a person or machine": "",
  "Net force is the overall force on an object after all individual forces are combined (added as vectors). When forces act in the same direction they add together; when they act in opposite directions they partially cancel. If the net force is zero, the object does not accelerate.": "",
  "Define the term 'equilibrium' as it applies to forces.": "",
  "A condition where all forces are as large as possible": "",
  "A condition where the net force on an object is zero": "",
  "A condition where only gravity acts on the object": "",
  "A condition where all motion has completely stopped": "",
  "Equilibrium means the net force acting on an object is zero (ΣF = 0). This does not require the object to be at rest — it can be moving at constant velocity. The key requirement is that all forces balance out so there is no acceleration.": "",
  "What is the meaning of the term 'vector' in physics?": "",
  "A quantity that has only magnitude and no direction": "",
  "A quantity that has both magnitude and direction": "",
  "A unit of measurement used for temperature": "",
  "A type of graph used to display force data": "",
  "A vector is a quantity that has both magnitude (size or amount) and direction. Force, velocity, and acceleration are all vectors. By contrast, scalars such as mass, speed, and temperature have magnitude only.": "",
  "What does the term 'applied force' refer to?": "",
  "The gravitational pull from Earth on an object": "",
  "A push or pull exerted on an object by a person or another object": "",
  "The upward force a surface exerts on an object": "",
  "The resistance an object encounters from the air": "",
  "An applied force is a push or pull that is directly exerted on an object by a person, machine, or another object in contact with it. Examples include pushing a cart or pulling a wagon. It is a contact force.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'gravity' as a force?": "",
  "A contact force that requires objects to touch each other": "",
  "A force that only acts on very heavy objects in space": "",
  "An attractive force between any two objects that have mass": "",
  "A repulsive force that pushes objects apart from each other": "",
  "Gravity is a non-contact, attractive force that exists between any two objects with mass. On Earth's surface, gravitational acceleration is approximately 9.8 m/s². The weight of an object equals its mass times gravitational acceleration (W = mg).": "",
  "What does the term 'balanced forces' mean?": "",
  "Forces that cause an object to accelerate quickly": "",
  "Forces that are equal in size but act in the same direction": "",
  "Forces that cancel out so the net force is zero": "",
  "Forces that only act on objects that are not moving": "",
  "Balanced forces are forces that are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction, resulting in a net force of zero. When forces are balanced, the object's motion does not change — it stays at rest or continues moving at constant velocity.": "",
  "What does the term 'unbalanced forces' describe?": "",
  "Forces that perfectly cancel each other out": "",
  "Forces that result in a nonzero net force and cause acceleration": "",
  "Forces that are too small to have any measurable effect": "",
  "Forces that only exist in the absence of gravity": "",
  "Unbalanced forces do not cancel out, producing a nonzero net force. According to Newton's Second Law, a nonzero net force causes an object to accelerate — it speeds up, slows down, or changes direction.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'air resistance'?": "",
  "A force that pushes objects upward against gravity": "",
  "A contact force that opposes an object's motion through air": "",
  "A non-contact force that attracts nearby air particles": "",
  "A force created only when the wind is blowing outside": "",
  "Air resistance (also called drag) is a contact force that opposes the motion of an object as it moves through air. It depends on the object's speed, shape, and surface area. Faster objects and larger surface areas experience more air resistance.": "",
  "What does 'magnitude' mean when describing a force?": "",
  "The direction in which the force is applied": "",
  "The size or strength of the force in Newtons": "",
  "The type of force such as gravity or friction": "",
  "The object on which the force is being exerted": "",
  "Magnitude refers to the size or strength of a force, expressed as a number with units (Newtons). For example, a 10 N force has a magnitude of 10 N. Since force is a vector, you need both magnitude and direction to fully describe it.": "",
  "A student places a book on a table. The book does not move. What can the student conclude about the forces on the book?": "",
  "No forces are acting on the book at all": "",
  "Only gravity is acting on the book right now": "",
  "The forces on the book are balanced so the net force is zero": "",
  "The table is pushing the book upward harder than gravity pulls it down": "",
  "A stationary book on a table has two main forces: gravity pulling it down and the normal force pushing it up. Since the book is not accelerating, these forces are balanced and the net force is zero. Forces still act on the book — they simply cancel out.": "",
  "In a lab, two students push a cart in opposite directions. Student A pushes with 20 N to the right, and Student B pushes with 15 N to the left. What is the net force on the cart?": "",
  "35 N to the right": "",
  "5 N to the right": "",
  "5 N to the left": "",
  "35 N to the left": "",
  "When forces act in opposite directions, the net force is the difference between them and points in the direction of the larger force. Here: 20 N (right) − 15 N (left) = 5 N to the right. The cart accelerates to the right.": "",
  "A student draws a free-body diagram for a falling skydiver. Which forces should appear on the diagram?": "",
  "Only the force of gravity pointing downward": "",
  "Gravity pointing downward and air resistance pointing upward": "",
  "Normal force pointing upward and gravity pointing downward": "",
  "Thrust pointing downward and friction pointing sideways": "",
  "A falling skydiver has two forces: gravity pulling downward and air resistance (drag) pushing upward against the direction of motion. There is no normal force because the skydiver is not touching a surface, and there is no thrust.": "",
  "A student pushes a box across the floor with a steady 30 N force. The box moves at a constant speed. What is the friction force on the box?": "",
  "0 N because the box is already moving": "",
  "30 N opposing the direction of motion": "",
  "60 N opposing the direction of motion": "",
  "15 N opposing the direction of motion": "",
  "Constant speed means zero acceleration, which means the net force is zero. If the student pushes with 30 N forward, friction must be exactly 30 N backward to balance it out. The forces are balanced even though the box is moving.": "",
  "In a tug-of-war, Team A pulls with 500 N to the left and Team B pulls with 450 N to the right. Which way does the rope move?": "",
  "The rope does not move because the forces cancel": "",
  "The rope moves to the left toward Team A": "",
  "The rope moves to the right toward Team B": "",
  "The rope moves upward away from both teams": "",
  "The net force is 500 N − 450 N = 50 N to the left. Since the forces are unbalanced, the rope accelerates in the direction of the larger force — toward Team A on the left.": "",
  "A student holds a ball in her hand without moving. She then opens her hand and the ball falls. What force caused the ball to start moving?": "",
  "An applied force from her hand pushing the ball down": "",
  "The unbalanced gravitational force once the normal force was removed": "",
  "Air resistance pushing the ball toward the ground below": "",
  "Friction between the ball and the surrounding air molecules": "",
  "While the student held the ball, gravity and the normal force from her hand were balanced. When she opened her hand, the normal force disappeared, leaving gravity as an unbalanced force. The ball then accelerated downward.": "",
  "A soccer player kicks a ball on a grass field. The ball gradually slows down and stops. Which force is mainly responsible for stopping the ball?": "",
  "The gravitational pull of the Earth on the ball": "",
  "Friction between the ball and the grass surface": "",
  "The normal force from the ground pushing upward": "",
  "The tension in the grass blades pulling on the ball": "",
  "Friction is a contact force that opposes the relative motion between two surfaces. As the ball rolls on the grass, friction acts opposite to its direction of motion, gradually slowing it down until it stops.": "",
  "A student notices that a magnet attracts a paper clip from across a table without touching it. What type of force is the magnet exerting?": "",
  "A contact force because the magnet moves the clip": "",
  "A non-contact force because it acts over a distance": "",
  "A frictional force between the clip and the table": "",
  "A gravitational force between the clip and the magnet": "",
  "Magnetic force is a non-contact force because the magnet can attract or repel objects without physically touching them. Non-contact forces — including gravity, magnetic force, and electric force — can act across a distance.": "",
  "In a lab experiment, a student measures two forces acting on a toy car: 8 N to the east and 8 N to the west. What happens to the car?": "",
  "The car accelerates to the east due to the first force": "",
  "The car accelerates to the west due to the second force": "",
  "The car does not accelerate because the net force is zero": "",
  "The car spins in a circle from the two equal forces": "",
  "When two equal forces act in opposite directions, they cancel each other out. The net force is 8 N − 8 N = 0 N. With zero net force, the car does not accelerate — it either stays at rest or continues at constant velocity.": "",
  "A student is riding a bicycle and suddenly applies the brakes. The bike slows down. What is the main contact force responsible for slowing the bicycle?": "",
  "Gravity pulling the bicycle toward the ground below": "",
  "The normal force from the road pushing the tires upward": "",
  "The magnetic force between the brake pads and the wheel": "",
  "Friction between the brake pads and the wheel rim": "",
  "When the student squeezes the brakes, the brake pads press against the wheel rim, creating friction. This friction force opposes the wheel's rotation and slows the bicycle down. Friction is a contact force that requires physical touch between surfaces.": ""
